{{About||the Hebrew Half-Shekel|Shekel#Collection of the half-Shekel}} [[File:Dishekel hispano-cartaginés-2.jpg|thumb|A '''Carthaginian''' [[shekel]], dated 237-227 BC, depicting the Punic god [[Melqart]] (equivalent of [[Hercules]]/[[Heracles]]), most likely with the features of [[Hamilcar Barca]], father of Hannibal Barca; on the reverse is a man riding a [[war elephant]]]] [[File:Carthage EL shekel 2250013.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A {{circa|lk=no|300}}&nbsp;{{sc|bc}} [[Ancient Carthage|Carthaginian]] shekel bearing the wreathed head of [[Tanit]] and a standing [[horse]].]] [[File:CarthageElectrumCoin250BCE.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A {{circa|lk=no|250}}&nbsp;{{sc|bc}} [[electrum]] ([[silver]]-and-[[gold]]) [[Ancient Carthage|Carthaginian]] coin bearing the wreathed head of [[Tanit]].]] [[File:KMM - Schekel Karthago.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A [[silver]] [[Ancient Carthage|Carthaginian]] [[shekel]] bearing the wreathed head of [[Tanit]] and a standing horse before a [[palm tree]] and beside a star.]] [[File:CarthageBillion.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A {{circa|lk=no|210}}&nbsp;{{sc|bc}} [[Billon (alloy)|billon]] [[Ancient Carthage|Carthaginian]] [[tridrachm]] coin bearing the wreathed head of [[Tanit]].]] '''Carthaginian''' or '''Punic currency''' refers to the [[coin]]s of [[ancient Carthage]], a [[Phoenicia]]n [[city-state]] located near present-day [[Tunis]], [[Tunisia]]. __NOTOC__ {{anchor|Etymology}}
==Name== The base currency was the [[shekel]], although its [[Punic language|Punic]] pronunciation was probably {{IPA|/səˈḳel/}}.{{sfnp|Vennemann|2013b|p=487}}
==History== The [[Phoenicians]], despite their extensive [[Phoenician colonization|trading empire]]s, began minting coins relatively late. [[Sicily|Siculo]]-Carthaginian currency began to be issued in the mid-4th century and probably preceded [[Phoenicia]]'s own [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyrian]] [[Tyrian shekel|shekel]]s, which developed {{circa|lk=no|300}}&nbsp;{{sc|bc}}.{{sfnp|Bronson|1976|p=8}} Carthage was also the first known state to utilize lightweight, flexible leather promissory notes.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=huYoAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA34&lpg=PA34&dq=carthaginian+parchment+money&source=bl&ots=xe49nkFfpQ&sig=6KuFrBqpM-kANvnaoyUft_M_F8c&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjH792Y9IvUAhWK8YMKHYVjBlEQ6AEIPDAF#v=onepage&q=carthaginian%20parchment%20money&f=false|title=The Science of Money and American Finances: Containing a Philosophy of Money in Accordance with Scientific Principles, and Adapted to the Wants and Civilization of the Age. Also, an Analysis and History of the Financial Operations of the Government ...|last=Moulton|first=Luther Vanhorn|date=1880|publisher=Co-operative Press|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IW4vAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PA10&lpg=RA1-PA10&dq=carthaginian+parchment+money&source=bl&ots=R1FY0iuiEw&sig=VpFVxkqGa2blPKotlhyBjm56w0w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjH792Y9IvUAhWK8YMKHYVjBlEQ6AEIOTAE#v=onepage&q=carthaginian%20parchment%20money&f=false|title=Speeches of J.P. Jones: Money and Tariff, 1890-93|last=Jones|first=John Percival|date=1890|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/outlineofhistory00wellrich|title=The outline of history, being a plain history of life and mankind|last=Wells|first=H. G. (Herbert George)|date=1921|publisher=New York, The Macmillan Company}}</ref>
[[Ancient Carthage|Carthage]] issued ½-shekel,{{sfnp|Crawford|1985|p=137}} [[shekel]] (7.20&nbsp;[[gram|g]]),{{sfnp|Crawford|1985|p=87}} 1⅔-shekel, double shekel, and triple shekel coins.{{sfnp|Crawford|1985|p=135}} 5-shekel pieces were issued in Sicily.{{sfnp|Crawford|1985|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=84_G_8q6WQcC&pg=PA106 106]}} It used [[gold coin|gold]], [[silver]], [[electrum]], [[bronze]], and [[billon (alloy)|billon]] for its coins but did not make great use of them in [[North Africa]]. Instead, many of the surviving caches come from Carthage's holdings on [[Sardinia]] and [[Sicily]].{{sfnp|Crawford|1985|p=133}} On Sardinia, a substantial amount of bronze coinage was struck during the [[First Punic War]] and again during the attempt to recover the island amid the [[Second Punic War|Second]].{{sfnp|Crawford|1985|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=84_G_8q6WQcC&pg=PA103 103]}} A large mass of bronze and silver coins and smaller issues in gold and electrum were struck on [[Carthaginian Sicily|Sicily]] under administrators described as {{sc|mhsbm}}.{{sfnp|Crawford|1985|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=84_G_8q6WQcC&pg=PA104 104–5]}} The Siculo-Carthaginian issues of the First Punic War include one series featuring [[Melqart]] ("[[Hercules]]") [[obverse]] and a horse's head reverse.{{sfnp|Crawford|1985|p=[https://books.google.com/books?id=84_G_8q6WQcC&pg=PA106 106]}} More commonly, Carthaginian currency featured a female head identified as the [[Carthaginian religion|goddess]] [[Tanit]].{{sfnp|Vennemann|2013a}} One issue of bronze coins in two denominations—Tanit the god of sun on the obverse and a [[gallop]]ing [[horse]] [[obverse and reverse|reverse]]—was coined at Kerkouane on [[Cape Bon]] during the resistance to the invasion of [[Marcus Atilius Regulus|Regulus]] amid the [[First Punic War]].{{sfnp|Crawford|1985|p=133}} A great deal of highly debased<!--sic--> coins were struck at the end of the First Punic War, however, to deal with the empire's revolting mercenaries.{{sfnp|Crawford|1985|p=136}}
Between the [[First Punic War|First]] and [[Second Punic War]]s, Carthage only issued bronze coins in North Africa,{{sfnp|Crawford|1985|p=136}} although the [[Barcids]] issued gold and silver coins in [[Carthaginian Spain|Spain]]{{sfnp|Crawford|1985|p=87}} bearing the head of [[Melqart]] [[obverse]] and a horse and [[palm tree]] reverse.{{sfnp|Crawford|1985|p=88}} The gold coins were produced at a weight of 7.50&nbsp;[[gram|g]], reflecting a value of 12 silver shekels each at a [[bullion]] exchange rate of 1:11⅓.{{sfnp|Crawford|1985|p=87}} Spanish expansion and Roman plunder permitted issues in precious metals during the [[Second Punic War]],{{sfnp|Crawford|1985|p=136}} including two large silver issues for use on Sicily.{{sfnp|Crawford|1985|p=109}} One set of half-shekels featured a [[diadem]]ed male head [[obverse]] and [[Hannibal's crossing of the Alps|elephant]] reverse; another featured a male head with grain wreath [[obverse]] and a galloping horse reverse.{{sfnp|Crawford|1985|p=108}} By the war's end, bronze was again being used{{sfnp|Crawford|1985|p=136}} and, following the war, debased silver.{{sfnp|Crawford|1985|p=138}} The shekel also decreased in Barcid areas from 7.2 to around 7.0&nbsp;[[gram|g]] over the course of the war.{{sfnp|Crawford|1985|p=87}} Bronze coins similarly varied in weight between 8 and 10&nbsp;[[gram|g]] owing to varying exchange rates between it and the silver currency.{{sfnp|Crawford|1985|p=87}} The last issues before the [[Third Punic War]] attest to the city's revitalization, as they are again pure silver{{sfnp|Crawford|1985|p=138}} with a serrate edge.{{sfnp|Crawford|1985|p=139}}
[[Numidia]]n coins also circulated but were entirely of bronze.{{sfnp|Crawford|1985|p=140}}
Recently, it has been proposed that the Germanic ''[[penny]]'', ''{{lang|sv|[[Swedish penning|penning]]}}'', ''{{lang|de|[[Pfennig]]}}'', &c. may derive from an early borrowing of [[Punic language|Punic]] {{lang|xpu|{{sc|pn}}}} (''Pane'' or ''Pene'', "Face"), as the face of [[Religion in Carthage|Carthaginian]] [[List of fertility deities|fertility goddess]] [[Tanit]] was represented on nearly all Carthaginian currency.{{sfnp|Vennemann|2013a|p=467}} The theory is, however, still disputed. Similarly, the supposed discovery of a [[Carthaginian coins of Corvo|cache of Carthaginian coins]] on [[Corvo Island|Corvo]] in 1749 is the basis for supposing that the [[Carthaginians]] reached the [[Azores Islands|Azores]], but remains contentious.<ref>{{citation |last=Bikai |first=Pierre M. |author2=Patricia M. Bikai |display-authors=1 |contribution-url=http://nautarch.tamu.edu/shiplab/acores-geral01-fenicios.htm |title=Archaeology |date=January 1990 |contribution=Timelines: A Phoenician Fable }}.</ref>
==Remains== A collection of recovered coins is maintained at the Tunisian Mint Museum ({{lang-fr|Musée de la Monnaie en Tunisie}}) at the [[Central Bank of Tunisia|Central Bank]] in [[Tunis]].<ref>{{citation |title=The Central Bank of Tunisia |contribution=Museum |contribution-url=http://www.bct.gov.tn/bct/siteprod/page.jsp?id=999&la=AN |accessdate=9 February 2016 }}.</ref>
