{{Infobox member of the Knesset | image=PikiWiki Israel 28630 Art of Israel (cropped).jpg | birth_date = {{Birth date|1926|6|19|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Jerusalem]], [[Mandatory Palestine]] | Year of Aliyah = | death_date = {{Death date and age|2015|9|15|1926|6|19|df=y}} | death_place = [[Tel Aviv]], Israel | Knesset(s) = [[Israeli legislative election, 1973|8]], [[Israeli legislative election, 1977|9]] | party1 = [[Moked]] | partyyears1 = 1974–1977 | party2 = [[Left Camp of Israel]] | partyyears2 = 1977–1980 }}
'''Meir Pa'il''' ({{lang-he-n|מאיר פעיל}}&lrm;; 19 June 1926 &ndash; 15 September 2015) was a colonel in the [[Israel Defense Forces]], an Israeli politician, and military historian.
==Biography== Pa'il was born in [[Jerusalem]] during the [[Mandatory Palestine|Mandate era]] as '''Meir Pilevsky'''. His parents, Nahum and Bracha Pilevsky, were pioneers of the [[Third Aliyah]]. Pa'il studied at the Tahkemoni school in Jerusalem, a school for laborer's children in [[Holon]], and at Balfour high school in [[Tel Aviv]]. He joined the "Working Youth" movement in 1937 and served in an active signal unit for the [[Haganah]].
Pa'il served in the [[Palmach]] from 1943-48. He participated in a series of operations, including the smuggling of illegal Jewish immigrants from Syria and Lebanon, the [[The Hunting Season|Saison]], the [[Night of the Bridges]], and an attack on a British police position on Mount Canaan. During the [[1948 Arab-Israeli War]], Pa'il served in the [[Negev Brigade]]. Pa'il served as a career officer in the IDF, commanding the 51st Battalion during the [[Suez Crisis]], the Bahad-1 officers school from 1964-1966, and the Department of Military Theory for the General Staff. He left the IDF in 1971.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/israel/.premium-1.676088|title=Veteran Israeli Politician and Career Soldier, Meir Pa'il, Dies at 89|first=Ofer|last=Aderet|date=16 September 2015|publisher=|via=Haaretz}}</ref>
Pa'il studied history and Middle Eastern studies at [[Tel Aviv University]], later gaining a doctorate in military and general history.{{cn|date=April 2018}} In 1973, he was among the founders of the [[Blue-Red Movement]], which merged with [[Maki (political party)|Maki]] to form [[Moked]], which Pa'il headed.{{cn|date=April 2018}}
He was elected to the Knesset in the [[Israeli legislative election, 1973|1973 elections]] on the [[Moked]] list, and was the party's only representative in the [[Knesset]]. The party merged with several others to form the [[Left Camp of Israel]] prior to the [[Israeli legislative election, 1977|1977 elections]]. The new party won two seats, which were rotated between five party members including Pa'il. However, they failed to win any seats in the [[Israeli legislative election, 1981|1981 elections]] and Pa'il did not reappear in the Knesset. He died on September 15, 2015 due to complications of [[Alzheimer's disease]].<ref name="YNN">{{cite news|url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-4700597,00.html|title=Former MK Meir Pa'il passes away at 89|date=15 September 2015|publisher=[[Ynetnews]]|accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref>
==Published works== *''Political and Military Reflections in the Wake of the War of October 1973''. Tel Aviv: Israel Peace Research Society, 1974. {{OCLC|3560340}} *''From the Hagana to the IDF'' (1979) (Hebrew) *''The West Bank and Gaza: A Strategic Analysis for Peace''. Tel-Aviv: New Outlook, 1981. {{OCLC|7899345}} *''Development of Jewish Defense Capabilities, 1907–1948'' (1987) (Hebrew) *''Independence 1948'' (1990) (Hebrew) *''Rift in 1948'' (1990) *''The Palmach'' (1995) (Hebrew) *'' From Hashomer to the Israel Defence Forces: Armed Jewish Defense in Palestine''. Jerusalem: Israel Information Center, 1997. {{OCLC|751545036}} *''The Commander: Temperate Military Leadership'' (2003) (Hebrew) <ref>{{cite news | last = Dromi | first = Uri | date = 3 October 2003 | title = No Longer Pure and Simple - review of "The Commander: Temperate Military Leadership" by Meir Pa'il | url = http://www.haaretz.com/life/books/no-longer-pure-and-simple-1.101786 | newspaper = Haaretz | location = Israel | access-date = 15 September 2015 }}</ref> *''Meirke - Meir Pa'il: Commander, Educator, Historian, Politician - Autobiography and Selected Texts''. (2014) (Hebrew) {{OCLC| 891845270}}
